Min-max 
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>Fixed Width Example</title>
  <style>
    .fixed-width {
      min-width: 20px;
      max-width: 20px;
      background-color: lightblue;
      height: 50px;
      text-align: center;
      line-height: 50px;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <div class="fixed-width">20px</div>
</body>
</html>


Explanation:
CSS Properties Used:

min-width: 20px;: This sets the minimum width the element can have to 20px.
max-width: 20px;: This sets the maximum width the element can have to 20px.
By combining both properties with the same value, the width is effectively locked to 20px.

Additional Styles:

background-color: lightblue;: Gives the element a background color so you can easily see it.
height: 50px;: Sets the height of the element to make it visually noticeable.
text-align: center; and line-height: 50px;: Centers the text vertically and horizontally within the element.
Outcome: The <div> will always be 20px wide regardless of the screen size or content. Even if the browser window is resized or the content inside grows larger, the width remains fixed.
