Flex
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <style>
    .container {
      display: flex;
      
      background-color: lightgray;
      height: 500px;
      justify-content: space-around;
      align-items: center;
    }
    .box {
      background-color: lightblue;
      padding: 20px;
      margin: 5px;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <div class="container">
    <div class="box">Box 1</div>
    <div class="box">Box 2</div>
    <div class="box">Box 3</div>
    
    <div class="box">Box 3</div>
    <div class="box">Box 4</div>
    <div class="box">Box 5</div>
  </div>
</body>
</html>
Flex (short for Flexible Box Layout) is a CSS layout model used to create responsive and 
flexible web page designs. It helps arrange items in a row or column and makes them automatically adjust 
their size based on the available space.





Explanation of Properties Used:
display: flex;

Makes the container a flex container, enabling Flexbox layout for its children.
justify-content: center;

Aligns items horizontally.
Options:
flex-start: Aligns items to the left.
flex-end: Aligns items to the right.
center: Centers items horizontally.
space-between: Adds equal space between items.
space-around: Adds equal space around items.
align-items: center;

Aligns items vertically in the container.
Options:
stretch (default): Stretches items to fill the container height.
center: Centers items vertically.
flex-start: Aligns items to the top.
flex-end: Aligns items to the bottom.
margin: 5px;

Adds space around each box for separation.


------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
flex-grow shrink


<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <style>
    .container {
      display: flex;
      width: 600px; /* Fixed width for demonstration */
      background-color: lightgray;
    }
    .box {
      background-color: lightblue;
      margin: 5px;
      text-align: center;
      line-height: 50px;
      height: 50px;
    }
    .grow {
      flex-grow: 2; /* This item will grow twice as much as others */
    }
    .shrink {
      flex-shrink: 2; /* This item will shrink twice as much as others */
    }
    .normal {
      flex-grow: 1; /* Default grow */
      flex-shrink: 1; /* Default shrink */
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <div class="container">
    <div class="box normal" style="width: 10px;">Box 1</div>
    <div class="box grow" style="width: 10px;">Box 2</div>
    <div class="box shrink" style="width: 20px;">Box 3</div>
  </div>
</body>
</html>

Understanding flex-grow and flex-shrink in Simple Terms:
Flexbox allows items to expand (flex-grow) or shrink (flex-shrink) to fit within the available space of their container.

1. flex-grow: Controls how much an item grows (expands) if there's extra space in the container.
A higher flex-grow value means the item will take more of the available space.
If all items have the same flex-grow value, they grow equally.
2. flex-shrink: Controls how much an item shrinks when the container is too small.
A higher flex-shrink value means the item will shrink more than others.
If all items have the same flex-shrink value, they shrink equally.


Explanation:
flex-grow Example:

Box 1 (normal) has flex-grow: 1.
Box 2 (grow) has flex-grow: 2, so it grows twice as much as Box 1 when there's extra space.
When the container has extra space, Box 2 becomes larger than the others.
flex-shrink Example:

Box 3 (shrink) has flex-shrink: 2.
If the container width becomes smaller (less than 600px), Box 3 shrinks twice as much as the others.
Key Points:
flex-grow:

If no extra space is available, it has no effect.
Used for distributing extra space.
flex-shrink:

If there's no need to shrink (e.g., container is large enough), it has no effect.
Used when items need to "give up" space due to a lack of room.
Result:
Initially, Box 2 will be the largest because of flex-grow: 2.
If the browser window is resized smaller than 600px:
Box 3 shrinks the most because it has flex-shrink: 2.
You can copy the code, try it in a browser, and resize the window to observe the behavior!
--------------------------------------------------------------------
What Are Gradients in CSS?
A gradient in CSS is a smooth transition between two or more colors. It can be used to create background images, buttons, or other design elements. Gradients are typically used when you want to create a visually appealing blend of colors without the need for a solid image file.

There are two main types of gradients in CSS:

Linear Gradient: Transitions colors along a straight line.
Radial Gradient: Transitions colors in a circular pattern, originating from a central point.
1. Linear Gradient
A linear gradient transitions colors along a straight line. You can control the direction of the gradient (e.g., top-to-bottom, left-to-right).

Syntax:
css
Copy
Edit
background: linear-gradient(direction, color1, color2, ...);
direction: The direction of the gradient (e.g., to right, to bottom, 45deg).
color1, color2, ...: The colors that blend into each other.
Example:
html
Copy
Edit
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>Linear Gradient Example</title>
  <style>
    .linear-gradient {
      height: 200px;
      background: linear-gradient(to right, red, yellow);
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <div class="linear-gradient"></div>
</body>
</html>
to right: This creates a gradient that goes from left to right.
red, yellow: The gradient starts with red and ends with yellow.
2. Radial Gradient
A radial gradient transitions colors from a central point outward, like ripples on water.

Syntax:
css
Copy
Edit
background: radial-gradient(shape size at position, color1, color2, ...);
shape: Defines the shape of the gradient, usually circle or ellipse.
size: Defines the size of the gradient, such as closest-side, farthest-side, etc.
position: Defines the starting point of the gradient, like center, top, etc.
color1, color2, ...: The colors that blend in the gradient.
Example:
html
Copy
Edit
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>Radial Gradient Example</title>
  <style>
    .radial-gradient {
      height: 200px;
      background: radial-gradient(circle, blue, green, yellow);
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <div class="radial-gradient"></div>
</body>
</html>
circle: The gradient will form in a circular shape.
blue, green, yellow: The gradient starts with blue at the center, transitions to green, and finally ends with yellow.
3. Multi-Color Gradients
You can add more than two colors to create a gradient with multiple color stops.

Example:
css
Copy
Edit
background: linear-gradient(to bottom, red, orange, yellow, green, blue);
This will create a vertical gradient that transitions through five colors (red ‚Üí orange ‚Üí yellow ‚Üí green ‚Üí blue).

