<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Transform and Transition</title>
    <style>
        .box {
            width: 100px;
            height: 100px;
            background-color: lightblue;
            margin: 50px auto;
            text-align: center;
            line-height: 100px;
            color: white;
            font-weight: bold;
            border-radius: 10px;

            /* Adding transformation and transition effects */
            transform: rotate(0deg) scale(1, 1); /* Default state */
            transition: height 1s ease-in-out 0.5s, transform 0.5s ease-in-out;
        }

        /* Rotate and scale on hover */
        .box:hover {
            transform: rotate(120deg) scale(2, 3); /* Rotate 120 degrees and scale */
            height: 200px; /* Smooth height change */
            background-color: lightcoral; /* To show changes more clearly */
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Transform and Transition Example</h1>
    <div class="box">Hover me!</div>
</body>
</html>


Explanation:
Default State (.box):

transform: rotate(0deg) scale(1, 1);:
No rotation.
No scaling; the element is displayed at its original size.
transition: height 1s ease-in-out 0.5s, transform 0.5s ease-in-out;:
Height: Changes smoothly over 1 second with a 0.5-second delay.
Transform: Changes smoothly over 0.5 seconds.
On Hover (.box:hover):

transform: rotate(120deg) scale(2, 3);:
Rotates the element 120 degrees.
Scales its width 2 times and height 3 times.
height: 200px;:
Increases the height to 200px with a smooth transition.
Visual Feedback:

When you hover over the box:
The height increases smoothly after a slight delay (0.5 seconds).
The box rotates 120 degrees and scales up simultaneously.
The background color changes for better visualization.
How It Works:
Open the page in a browser.
Hover over the box to see the rotation, scaling, and height change animations.
The transform and transition properties work together to create smooth effects.
Let me know if you want to add more effects or tweak the example!


